## The Svelte logic

This is where Tailwind meets a real framework. A single `$state` rune holds the current step;
Svelte's `{#if}` blocks swap the step content; the progress bar maps over the step count.

<CodeBlock language="svelte" filename="MultiStepForm.svelte" code={stepperLogic} />

Notice how little code drives the whole flow — the styling is utilities, the logic is a handful of
runes. That separation is exactly what makes this maintainable.

<Callout type="insight" title="State lives in the framework; presentation lives in utilities">

The clean architecture here is worth internalising: **Svelte owns *what* is shown (step, validity,
data); Tailwind owns *how* it looks.** The dynamic class `i < step ? 'bg-indigo-600' : 'bg-slate-200'`
is the bridge — a tiny expression that maps state to style. As components grow, keep this separation
crisp: when you find yourself encoding business logic in class strings, or visual constants in your
script, pause and re-draw the line. Clear boundaries are what keep components understandable a year
later.

</Callout>

<Callout type="warning" title="Don't lose accessibility in the steps">

When the active step changes, move focus to the new step's heading (or first field) and consider an
`aria-live` region announcing "Step 2 of 3." Visual progress isn't enough for screen-reader users —
they need the change announced.

</Callout>

## Knowledge check

<Quiz
	question="In this design, what is the right home for the current step number?"
	options={[
		{ text: 'A Tailwind class on the container', correct: false },
		{ text: 'A Svelte $state rune in the component script', correct: true },
		{ text: 'A CSS variable', correct: false },
		{ text: 'The URL only', correct: false }
	]}
	explanation="State belongs in the framework ($state); utilities render it. Keep that boundary clean."
/>

